# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: racket
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:racket/guide-intro] Where there is no room for confusion, we use simply Racket.
[src:racket/guide-intro] Most likely, you’ll want to explore the Racket language using DrRacket, especially at the beginning.
[src:racket/guide-intro] If you prefer, you can also work with the command-line racket interpreter (see Running racket and gracket) and your favorite text editor (see Command-Line Tools and Your Editor of Choice).
[src:racket/guide-intro] The rest of this guide presents the language mostly independent of your choice of editor.
[src:racket/guide-intro] If you’re using DrRacket, you’ll need to choose the proper language, because DrRacket accommodates many different variants of Racket, as well as other languages.
[src:racket/guide-intro] in DrRacket’s top text area, and then click the Run button that’s above the text area.
[src:racket/guide-intro] DrRacket then understands that you mean to work in the normal variant of Racket (as opposed to the smaller racket/base or many other possibilities).
[src:racket/guide-intro] If you’ve used DrRacket before with something other than a program that starts #lang, DrRacket will remember the last language that you used, instead of inferring the language from the #lang line.
[src:racket/guide-intro] In that case, use the Language|Choose Language... menu item.
[src:racket/guide-intro] In the dialog that appears, select the first item, which tells DrRacket to use the language that is declared in a source program via #lang.
[src:racket/guide-intro] Put the #lang line above in the top text area, still.
[src:racket/guide-intro] DrRacket’s bottom text area and the racket command-line program (when started with no options) both act as a kind of calculator.
[src:racket/guide-intro] You type a Racket expression, hit the Return key, and the answer is printed.
[src:racket/guide-intro] In the terminology of Racket, this kind of calculator is called a read-eval-print loop or REPL.
[src:racket/guide-intro] A string is also an expression that evaluates to itself.
[src:racket/guide-intro] Racket uses parentheses to wrap larger expressions—almost any kind of expression, other than simple constants.
[src:racket/guide-intro] For example, a function call is written: open parenthesis, function name, argument expression, and closing parenthesis.
[src:racket/guide-intro] Although you can evaluate the define form in the REPL, definitions are normally a part of a program that you want to keep and use later.
[src:racket/guide-intro] If calling (extract "the boy") is part of the main action of your program, that would go in the definitions area, too.
[src:racket/guide-intro] But if it was just an example expression that you were using to explore extract, then you’d more likely leave the definitions area as above, click Run, and then evaluate (extract "the boy") in the REPL.
[src:racket/guide-intro] When using command-line racket instead of DrRacket, you’d save the above text in a file using your favorite editor.
[src:racket/guide-intro] The enter! form both loads the code and switches the evaluation context to the inside of the module, just like DrRacket’s Run button.
[src:racket/guide-intro] then it is a complete program that prints “cat” when run.
[src:racket/guide-intro] That will work, because racket is willing to imitate a traditional Lisp environment, but we strongly recommend against using load or writing programs outside of a module.
[src:racket/guide-intro] Writing definitions outside of a module leads to bad error messages, bad performance, and awkward scripting to combine and run programs.
[src:racket/guide-intro] The problems are not specific to racket; they’re fundamental limitations of the traditional top-level environment, which Scheme and Lisp implementations have historically fought with ad hoc command-line flags, compiler directives, and build tools.
[src:racket/guide-intro] The module system is designed to avoid these problems, so start with #lang, and you’ll be happier with Racket in the long run.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket is used by the ProgramByDesign outreach program, which aims to turn computer science into "an indispensable part of the liberal arts curriculum".
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The core Racket language is known for its extensive macro system which enables creating embedded and domain-specific languages, language constructs such as classes or modules, and separate dialects of Racket with different semantics.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The platform distribution is free and open-source software distributed under the Apache 2.0 and MIT licenses.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Extensions and packages written by the community may be uploaded to Racket's package catalog.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Matthias Felleisen founded PLT Inc. in the mid 1990s, first as a research group, soon after as a project dedicated to producing pedagogic materials for novice programmers (lectures, exercises/projects, software).
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] In January 1995, the group decided to develop a pedagogic programming environment based on Scheme.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Matthew Flatt cobbled together MrEd, the original virtual machine for Racket, from libscheme, wxWidgets, and a few other free systems.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] In the years that followed, a team including Flatt, Robby Findler, Shriram Krishnamurthi, Cormac Flanagan, and many others produced DrScheme, a programming environment for novice Scheme programmers and a research environment for gradual typing.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The main development language that DrScheme supported was named PLT Scheme.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] In parallel, the team began conducting workshops for high school teachers, training them in program design and functional programming.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Field tests with these teachers and their students provided essential clues for directing the development.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Over the following years, PLT added teaching languages, an algebraic stepper, a transparent read–eval–print loop, a constructor-based printer, and many other innovations to DrScheme, producing an application-quality pedagogic program development environment.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] By 2001, the core team (Felleisen, Findler, Flatt, Krishnamurthi) had also written and published their first textbook, *How to Design Programs*, based on their teaching philosophy.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The first generation of PLT Scheme revisions introduced features for programming in the large with both modules and classes.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 42 introduced units – a first-class module system – to complement classes for large scale development.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The class system gained features (e.g., Java-style interfaces) and also lost several features (e.g. multiple inheritance) throughout these versions.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The language evolved throughout a number of successive versions, and gaining milestone popularity in Version 53, leading to extensive work and the following Version 100, which would be equivalent to a "1.0" release in current popular version systems.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The next major revision was named Version 200, which introduced a new default module system that cooperates with macros.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] In particular, the module system ensures that run-time and compile-time computation are separated to support a "tower of languages".
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Unlike units, these modules are not first-class objects.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 300 introduced Unicode support, foreign library support, and refinements to the class system.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Later on, the 300 series improved the performance of the language runtime with an addition of a JIT compiler and a switch to a default generational garbage collection.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] By the next major release, the project had switched to a more conventional sequence-based version numbering.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 4.0 introduced the `#lang` shorthand to specify the language that a module is written in.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Further, the revision introduced immutable pairs and lists, support for fine-grained parallelism, and a statically-typed dialect.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] On 7 June 2010, PLT Scheme was renamed Racket.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The renaming coincided with the release of Version 5.0.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Subsequently, the graphical user interface (GUI) backend was rewritten in Racket from C++ in Version 5.1 using native UI toolkits on all platforms.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 5.2 included a background syntax checking tool, a new plotting library, a database library, and a new extended REPL.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 5.3 included a new submodule feature for optionally loaded modules, new optimization tools, a JSON library, and other features.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 5.3.1 introduced major improvements to DrRacket: the background syntax checker was turned on by default and a new documentation preview tool was added.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] In version 6.0, Racket released its second-generation package management system.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] As part of this development, the principal DrRacket and Racket repository was reorganized and split into a large set of small packages, making it possible to install a *minimal racket* and to install only those packages needed.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Version 7 of Racket was released with a new macro expander written in Racket as part the preparations for supporting moving to the Chez Scheme runtime system and supporting multiple runtime systems.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] On 19 November 2019, Racket 7.5 was released.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The license of Racket 7.5 was less restrictive.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] They use now either the Apache 2.0 license or the MIT license.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] On 13 February 2021, Racket 8.0 was released.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket 8.0 marks the first release where Racket with the Chez Scheme runtime system, known as Racket CS, is the default implementation.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket CS is faster, easier to maintain and develop, backward-compatible with existing Racket programs, and has better parallel garbage collection.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket's core language includes macros, modules, lexical closures, tail calls, delimited continuations, parameters (fluid variables), software contracts, green threads and OS threads, and more.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The language also comes with primitives, such as eventspaces and custodians, which control resource management and enables the language to act like an operating system for loading and managing other programs.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Further extensions to the language are created with the powerful macro system, which together with the module system and custom parsers can control all aspects of a language.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Most language constructs in Racket are implemented as macros in the base language.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] These include a mixin class system, a component (or module) system as expressive as opaque ascription in the ML module system, and pattern matching.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Further, the language features the first contract system for a higher-order programming language.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket's contract system is inspired by the Design by Contract work for Eiffel and extends it to work for higher-order values such as first-class functions, objects, reference cells, and so on.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] For example, an object that is checked by a contract can be ensured to make contract checks when its methods are eventually invoked.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket includes both bytecode and JIT (JIT) compilers.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The bytecode compiler produces an internal bytecode format run by the Racket virtual machine, and the JIT compiler translates bytecode to machine code at runtime.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Since 2004, the language has also shipped with PLaneT, a package manager that is integrated into the module system so that third-party libraries can be transparently imported and used.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Also, PLaneT has a built-in versioning policy to prevent dependency hell.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] At the end of 2014, much of Racket's code was moved into a new packaging system separate from the main code base.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] This new packaging system is serviced by a client program named *raco*.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The new package system provides fewer features than PLaneT; a blog post by Jay McCarthy on the Racket blog explains the rationale for the change and how to duplicate the older system.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The features that most clearly distinguish Racket from other languages in the Lisp family are its integrated language extensibility features that support building new domain-specific and general-purpose languages.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket's extensibility features are built into the module system to allow context-sensitive and module-level control over syntax.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] For example, the `#%app` syntactic form can be overridden to change the semantics of function application.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Similarly, the `#%module-begin` form allows arbitrary static analysis of the entire module.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Since any module can be used as a language, via the `#lang` notation, this effectively means that virtually any aspect of the language can be programmed and controlled.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The module-level extensibility features are combined with a Scheme-like hygienic macro system, which provides more features than Lisp's s-expression manipulation system, Scheme 84's hygienic extend-syntax macros, or R5RS's syntax-rules.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Indeed, it is fair to say that the macro system is a carefully tuned application programming interface (API) for compiler extensions.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Using this compiler API, programmers can add features and entire domain-specific languages in a manner that makes them completely indistinguishable from built-in language constructs.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The *macro* system in Racket has been used to construct entire language dialects.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] This includes Typed Racket, which is a gradually typed dialect of Racket that eases the migration from untyped to typed code, Lazy Racket—a dialect with lazy evaluation, and Hackett, which combines Haskell and Racket.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The pedagogical programming language Pyret was originally implemented in Racket.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Other dialects include FrTime (functional reactive programming), Scribble (documentation language), Slideshow (presentation language), and several languages for education.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket's core distribution provides libraries to aid the development of programming languages.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Such languages are not restricted to s-expression based syntax.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] In addition to conventional readtable-based syntax extensions, the directive `#lang` enables the invocation of arbitrary parsers, which can be implemented using the parser tools library.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] See Racket logic programming for an example of such a language.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The language platform provides a self-hosted IDE named DrRacket, a continuation-based web server, a graphical user interface, and other tools.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] As a viable scripting tool with libraries like common scripting languages, it can be used for scripting the Unix shell.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] It can parse command-line arguments and execute external tools.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] DrRacket (formerly DrScheme) is widely used among introductory computer science courses that teach Scheme or Racket and is lauded for its simplicity and appeal to beginner programmers.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The IDE was originally built for use with the TeachScheme! project (now ProgramByDesign), an outreach effort by Northeastern University and a number of affiliated universities for attracting high school students to computer science courses at the college level.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The editor provides highlighting for syntax and run-time errors, parenthesis matching, a debugger and an algebraic stepper.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Its student-friendly features include support for multiple "language levels" (Beginning Student, Intermediate Student and so on).
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] It also has integrated library support, and sophisticated analysis tools for advanced programmers.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Further, module-oriented programming is supported with the module browser, a contour view, integrated testing and coverage measurements, and refactoring support.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] It provides integrated, context-sensitive access to an extensive hyper-linked help system named "Help Desk".
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] DrRacket is available for Windows, macOS, Unix, and Linux with the X Window System and programs behave similarly on all these platforms.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] This program, taken from the Racket website, draws a Sierpinski triangle, nested to depth 8.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Using the `#lang` directive, a source file can be written in different dialects of Racket.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket currently has two implementations.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Both support Linux, Windows and MacOS on a variety of architectures and are supported as at version 8.8 (2023).
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The default implementation uses the Chez Scheme incremental compiler and runtime.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] The alternate implementation generates platform-independent bytecode and uses just-in-time compilation to generate machine code as it is loaded.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Apart from having a basis in programming language theory, Racket was designed as a general-purpose language for production systems.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket has several features useful for a commercial language, among them an ability to compile standalone executables under Windows, macOS, and Unix, a profiler and debugger included in the integrated development environment (IDE), and a unit testing framework.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket has been used for commercial projects and web applications.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] A notable example is the Hacker News website, which runs on Arc, which is developed in Racket.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Naughty Dog has used it as a scripting language in several video games.
[src:racket/racket-programming-language] Racket is used to teach students algebra through game design in the Bootstrap program.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme language is standardized in the official Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) standard and a *de facto* standard named the *Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme* (R*n*RS).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A widely implemented standard is R5RS (1998).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The most recently ratified standard of Scheme is "R7RS-small" (2013).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The more expansive and modular R6RS was ratified in 2007.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Both trace their descent from R5RS; the timeline below reflects the chronological order of ratification.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme started in the 1970s as an attempt to understand Carl Hewitt's Actor model, for which purpose Steele and Sussman wrote a "tiny Lisp interpreter" using Maclisp and then "added mechanisms for creating actors and sending messages".
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme was originally called "Schemer", in the tradition of other Lisp-derived languages such as Planner or *Conniver*.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The current name resulted from the authors' use of the ITS operating system, which limited filenames to two components of at most six characters each.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Currently, "Schemer" is commonly used to refer to a Scheme programmer.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A new language standardization process began at the 2003 Scheme workshop, with the goal of producing an R6RS standard in 2006.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This process broke with the earlier R*n*RS approach of unanimity.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] R6RS features a standard module system, allowing a split between the core language and libraries.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Several drafts of the R6RS specification were released, the final version being R5.97RS.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A successful vote resulted in ratifying the new standard, announced on August 28, 2007.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Currently the newest releases of various Scheme implementations support the R6RS standard.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] There is a portable reference implementation of the proposed implicitly phased libraries for R6RS, called psyntax, which loads and bootstraps itself properly on various older Scheme implementations.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A feature of R6RS is the record-type descriptor (RTD).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] When an RTD is created and used, the record type representation can show the memory layout.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] It also calculated object field bit mask and mutable Scheme object field bit masks, and helped the garbage collector know what to do with the fields without traversing the whole fields list that are saved in the RTD.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] RTD allows users to expand the basic RTD to create a new record system.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] R6RS introduces numerous significant changes to the language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The source code is now specified in Unicode, and a large subset of Unicode characters may now appear in Scheme symbols and identifiers, and there are other minor changes to the lexical rules.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Character data is also now specified in Unicode.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Many standard procedures have been moved to the new standard libraries, which themselves form a large expansion of the standard, containing procedures and syntactic forms that were formerly not part of the standard.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A new module system has been introduced, and systems for exception handling are now standardized.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Syntax-rules has been replaced with a more expressive syntactic abstraction facility (syntax-case) which allows the use of all of Scheme at macro expansion time.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Compliant implementations are now *required* to support Scheme's full numeric tower, and the semantics of numbers have been expanded, mainly in the direction of support for the IEEE 754 standard for floating point numerical representation.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard has caused controversy because some see it as a departure from the minimalist philosophy.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Two working groups were created to work on these two new versions of Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The Scheme Reports Process site has links to the working groups' charters, public discussions and issue tracking system.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The ninth draft of R7RS (small language) was made available on April 15, 2013.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A vote ratifying this draft closed on May 20, 2013, and the final report has been available since August 6, 2013, describing "the 'small' language of that effort: therefore it cannot be considered in isolation as the successor to R6RS".
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is primarily a functional programming language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] It shares many characteristics with other members of the Lisp programming language family.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's very simple syntax is based on s-expressions, parenthesized lists in which a prefix operator is followed by its arguments.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs thus consist of sequences of nested lists.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Lists are also the main data structure in Scheme, leading to a close equivalence between source code and data formats (homoiconicity).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme programs can easily create and evaluate pieces of Scheme code dynamically.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The reliance on lists as data structures is shared by all Lisp dialects.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits a rich set of list-processing primitives such as `cons`, `car` and `cdr` from its Lisp progenitors.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme uses strictly but dynamically typed variables and supports first class procedures.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Thus, procedures can be assigned as values to variables or passed as arguments to procedures.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This section concentrates mainly on innovative features of the language, including those features that distinguish Scheme from other Lisps.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Unless stated otherwise, descriptions of features relate to the R5RS standard.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In examples provided in this section, the notation "===> result" is used to indicate the result of evaluating the expression on the immediately preceding line.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This is the same convention used in R5RS.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is a very simple language, much easier to implement than many other languages of comparable expressive power.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This ease is attributable to the use of lambda calculus to derive much of the syntax of the language from more primitive forms.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] For instance of the 23 s-expression-based syntactic constructs defined in the R5RS Scheme standard, 14 are classed as derived or library forms, which can be written as macros involving more fundamental forms, principally lambda.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] : define, lambda, quote, if, define-syntax, let-syntax, letrec-syntax, syntax-rules, set!
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Example: a macro to implement `let` as an expression using `lambda` to perform the variable bindings.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Thus using `let` as defined above a Scheme implementation would rewrite "`(let ((a 1)(b 2)) (+ b a))`" as "`((lambda (a b) (+ b a)) 1 2)`", which reduces implementation's task to that of coding procedure instantiations.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In 1998, Sussman and Steele remarked that the minimalism of Scheme was not a conscious design goal, but rather the unintended outcome of the design process.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Like most modern programming languages and unlike earlier Lisps such as Maclisp, Scheme is lexically scoped: all possible variable bindings in a program unit can be analyzed by reading the text of the program unit without considering the contexts in which it may be called.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This contrasts with dynamic scoping which was characteristic of early Lisp dialects, because of the processing costs associated with the primitive textual substitution methods used to implement lexical scoping algorithms in compilers and interpreters of the day.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In those Lisps, it was fully possible for a reference to a free variable inside a procedure to refer to quite distinct bindings external to the procedure, depending on the context of the call.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The impetus to incorporate lexical scoping, which was an unusual scoping model in the early 1970s, into their new version of Lisp, came from Sussman's studies of ALGOL.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] He suggested that ALGOL-like lexical scoping mechanisms would help to realize their initial goal of implementing Carl Hewitt's Actor model in Lisp.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Alonzo Church's mathematical notation, the lambda calculus, has inspired Lisp's use of "lambda" as a keyword for introducing a procedure, as well as influencing the development of functional programming techniques involving the use of higher-order functions in Lisp.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] But early Lisps were not suitable expressions of the lambda calculus because of their treatment of free variables.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A formal lambda system has axioms and a complete calculation rule.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] It is helpful for the analysis using mathematical logic and tools.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In this system, calculation can be seen as a directional deduction.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The syntax of lambda calculus follows the recursive expressions from x, y, z, ...,parentheses, spaces, the period and the symbol λ.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The function of lambda calculation includes: First, serve as a starting point of powerful mathematical logic.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Second, it can reduce the requirement of programmers to consider the implementation details, because it can be used to imitate machine evaluation.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Finally, the lambda calculation created a substantial meta-theory.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The introduction of lexical scope resolved the problem by making an equivalence between some forms of lambda notation and their practical expression in a working programming language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] They introduced continuation-passing style along with their first description of Scheme in the first of the Lambda Papers, and in subsequent papers, they proceeded to demonstrate the raw power of this practical use of lambda calculus.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme inherits its block structure from earlier block structured languages, particularly ALGOL.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, blocks are implemented by three *binding constructs*: `let`, `let*` and `letrec`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Blocks can be nested to create arbitrarily complex block structures according to the need of the programmer.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The use of block structuring to create local bindings alleviates the risk of namespace collision that can otherwise occur.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The other variant, `letrec`, is designed to enable mutually recursive procedures to be bound to one another.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] All procedures bound in a single `letrec` may refer to one another by name, as well as to values of variables defined earlier in the same `letrec`, but they may not refer to *values* defined later in the same `letrec`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A variant of `let`, the "named let" form, has an identifier after the `let` keyword.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This binds the let variables to the argument of a procedure whose name is the given identifier and whose body is the body of the let form.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The body may be repeated as desired by calling the procedure.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The named let is widely used to implement iteration.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Like any procedure in Scheme, the procedure created in the named let is a first-class object.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme has an iteration construct, `do`, but it is more idiomatic in Scheme to use tail recursion to express iteration.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Standard-conforming Scheme implementations are required to optimize tail calls so as to support an unbounded number of active tail calls (R5RS sec.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] 3.5)—a property the Scheme report describes as *proper tail recursion*—making it safe for Scheme programmers to write iterative algorithms using recursive structures, which are sometimes more intuitive.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Tail recursive procedures and the *named `let`* form provide support for iteration using tail recursion.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Continuations in Scheme are first-class objects.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme provides the procedure `call-with-current-continuation` (also known as `call/cc`) to capture the current continuation by packing it up as an escape procedure bound to a formal argument in a procedure provided by the programmer.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] 6.4) First-class continuations enable the programmer to create non-local control constructs such as iterators, coroutines, and backtracking.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Continuations can be used to emulate the behavior of return statements in imperative programming languages.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The following function `find-first`, given function `func` and list `lst`, returns the first element `x` in `lst` such that `(func x)` returns true.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The following example, a traditional programmer's puzzle, shows that Scheme can handle continuations as first-class objects, binding them to variables and passing them as arguments to procedures.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In contrast to Common Lisp, all data and procedures in Scheme share a common namespace, whereas in Common Lisp functions and data have separate namespaces making it possible for a function and a variable to have the same name, and requiring special notation for referring to a function as a value.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This is sometimes known as the "Lisp-1 vs.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Lisp-2" distinction, referring to the unified namespace of Scheme and the separate namespaces of Common Lisp.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, the same primitives that are used to manipulate and bind data can be used to bind procedures.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] There is no equivalent of Common Lisp's `defun` and `#'` primitives.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This subsection documents design decisions that have been taken over the years which have given Scheme a particular character, but are not the direct outcomes of the original design.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme specifies a comparatively full set of numerical datatypes including complex and rational types, which is known in Scheme as the numerical tower (R5RS sec.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The standard treats these as abstractions, and does not commit the implementor to any particular internal representations.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Numbers may have the quality of exactness.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] An exact number can only be produced by a sequence of exact operations involving other exact numbers—inexactness is thus contagious.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The standard specifies that any two implementations must produce equivalent results for all operations resulting in exact numbers.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard specifies procedures `exact->inexact` and `inexact->exact` which can be used to change the exactness of a number.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] `inexact->exact` produces "the exact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] `exact->inexact` produces "the inexact number that is numerically closest to the argument".
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard omits these procedures from the main report, but specifies them as R5RS compatibility procedures in the standard library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard, Scheme implementations are not required to implement the whole numerical tower, but they must implement "a coherent subset consistent with both the purposes of the implementation and the spirit of the Scheme language" (R5RS sec.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The new R6RS standard does require implementation of the whole tower, and "exact integer objects and exact rational number objects of practically unlimited size and precision, and to implement certain procedures...so they always return exact results when given exact arguments" (R6RS sec.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Example 1: exact arithmetic in an implementation that supports exact rational complex numbers.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Example 2: Same arithmetic in an implementation that supports neither exact rational numbers nor complex numbers but does accept real numbers in rational notation.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Both implementations conform to the R5RS standard but the second does not conform to R6RS because it does not implement the full numerical tower.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme supports delayed evaluation through the `delay` form and the procedure `force`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The lexical context of the original definition of the promise is preserved, and its value is also preserved after the first use of `force`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The promise is only ever evaluated once.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] These primitives, which produce or handle values known as promises, can be used to implement advanced lazy evaluation constructs such as streams.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In the R6RS standard, these are no longer primitives, but instead, are provided as part of the R5RS compatibility library (rnrs r5rs (6)).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In R5RS, a suggested implementation of `delay` and `force` is given, implementing the promise as a procedure with no arguments (a thunk) and using memoization to ensure that it is only ever evaluated once, irrespective of the number of times `force` is called (R5RS sec.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] SRFI 41 enables the expression of both finite and infinite sequences with extraordinary economy.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Most Lisps specify an order of evaluation for procedure arguments.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] ev is a procedure that describes the argument passed to it, then returns the value of the argument.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In contrast with other Lisps, the appearance of an expression in the operator position (the first item) of a Scheme expression is quite legal, as long as the result of the expression in the operator position is a procedure.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In calling the procedure "+" to add 1 and 2, the expressions (ev +), (ev 1) and (ev 2) may be evaluated in any order, as long as the effect is not as if they were evaluated in parallel.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Thus the following three lines may be displayed in any order by standard Scheme when the above example code is executed, although the text of one line may not be interleaved with another because that would violate the sequential evaluation constraint.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In the R5RS standard and in later reports, the syntax of Scheme can easily be extended via the macro system.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The R5RS standard introduced a powerful hygienic macro system that allows the programmer to add new syntactic constructs to the language using a simple pattern matching sublanguage (R5RS sec 4.3).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Prior to this, the hygienic macro system had been relegated to an appendix of the R4RS standard, as a "high level" system alongside a "low level" macro system, both of which were treated as extensions to Scheme rather than an essential part of the language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of the hygienic macro system, also called `syntax-rules`, are required to respect the lexical scoping of the rest of the language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This is assured by special naming and scoping rules for macro expansion and avoids common programming errors that can occur in the macro systems of other programming languages.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] R6RS specifies a more sophisticated transformation system, `syntax-case`, which has been available as a language extension to R5RS Scheme for some time.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Invocations of macros and procedures bear a close resemblance—both are s-expressions—but they are treated differently.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] When the compiler encounters an s-expression in the program, it first checks to see if the symbol is defined as a syntactic keyword within the current lexical scope.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] If so, it then attempts to expand the macro, treating the items in the tail of the s-expression as arguments without compiling code to evaluate them, and this process is repeated recursively until no macro invocations remain.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] If it is not a syntactic keyword, the compiler compiles code to evaluate the arguments in the tail of the s-expression and then to evaluate the variable represented by the symbol at the head of the s-expression and call it as a procedure with the evaluated tail expressions passed as arguments to it.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Most Scheme implementations also provide additional macro systems.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Among popular ones are syntactic closures, explicit renaming macros and `define-macro`, a non-hygienic macro system similar to `defmacro` system provided in Common Lisp.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The inability to specify whether or not a macro is hygienic is one of the shortcomings of the macro system.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Alternative models for expansion such as scope sets provide a potential solution.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Prior to R5RS, Scheme had no standard equivalent of the `eval` procedure which is ubiquitous in other Lisps, although the first Lambda Paper had described `evaluate` as "similar to the LISP function EVAL" and the first Revised Report in 1978 replaced this with `enclose`, which took two arguments.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The second, third and fourth revised reports omitted any equivalent of `eval`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The reason for this confusion is that in Scheme with its lexical scoping the result of evaluating an expression depends on where it is evaluated.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the outer environment, where `name` is defined, the result is the sum of the operands.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] If it is evaluated in the inner environment, where the symbol "+" has been bound to the value of the procedure "*", the result is the product of the two operands.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] R5RS resolves this confusion by specifying three procedures that return environments and providing a procedure `eval` that takes an s-expression and an environment and evaluates the expression in the environment provided.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] 6.5) R6RS extends this by providing a procedure called `environment` by which the programmer can specify exactly which objects to import into the evaluation environment.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] `interaction-environment` is the interpreter's global environment.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In most dialects of Lisp including Common Lisp, by convention the value `NIL` evaluates to the value false in a Boolean expression.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, since the IEEE standard in 1991, all values except `#f`, including `NIL`'s equivalent in Scheme which is written as `'()`, evaluate to the value true in a Boolean expression.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Where the constant representing the Boolean value of true is `T` in most Lisps, in Scheme it is `#t`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme the primitive datatypes are disjoint.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Only one of the following predicates can be true of any Scheme object: `boolean?`, `pair?`, `symbol?`, `number?`, `char?`, `string?`, `vector?`, `port?`, `procedure?`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Within the numerical datatype, by contrast, the numerical values overlap.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] For example, an integer value satisfies all of the `integer?`, `rational?`, `real?`, `complex?` and `number?` predicates at the same time.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Type dependent equivalence operations also exist in Scheme: `string=?` and `string-ci=?` compare two strings (the latter performs a case-independent comparison); `char=?` and `char-ci=?` compare characters; `=` compares numbers.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Up to the R5RS standard, the standard comment in Scheme was a semicolon, which makes the rest of the line invisible to Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme's input and output is based on the *port* datatype.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] (R5RS sec 6.6) R5RS defines two default ports, accessible with the procedures `current-input-port` and `current-output-port`, which correspond to the Unix notions of standard input and standard output.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations also provide `current-error-port`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Redirection of input and standard output is supported in the standard, by standard procedures such as `with-input-from-file` and `with-output-to-file`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Most implementations provide string ports with similar redirection capabilities, enabling many normal input-output operations to be performed on string buffers instead of files, using procedures described in SRFI 6.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies much more sophisticated and capable port procedures and many new types of port.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The following examples are written in strict R5RS Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Example 5: As 2, but with using call-with-output-file to send output to a file.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Similar procedures are provided for input.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] R5RS Scheme provides the predicates `input-port?` and `output-port?`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] For character input and output, `write-char`, `read-char`, `peek-char` and `char-ready?` are provided.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] For writing and reading Scheme expressions, Scheme provides `read` and `write`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] On a read operation, the result returned is the end-of-file object if the input port has reached the end of the file, and this can be tested using the predicate `eof-object?`.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] With the standard, SRFI 28 also defines a basic formatting procedure resembling Common Lisp's `format` function, after which it is named.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In Scheme, procedures are bound to variables.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] At R5RS the language standard formally mandated that programs may change the variable bindings of built-in procedures, effectively redefining them.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS every binding, including the standard ones, belongs to some library, and all exported bindings are immutable.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] (R6RS sec 7.1) Because of this, redefinition of standard procedures by mutation is forbidden.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Instead, it is possible to import a different procedure under the name of a standard one, which in effect is similar to redefinition.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In Standard Scheme, procedures that convert from one datatype to another contain the character string "->" in their name, predicates end with a "?", and procedures that change the value of already-allocated data end with a "!".
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] These conventions are often followed by Scheme programmers.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In formal contexts such as Scheme standards, the word "procedure" is used in preference to "function" to refer to a lambda expression or primitive procedure.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In normal usage, the words "procedure" and "function" are used interchangeably.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Procedure application is sometimes referred to formally as *combination*.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] As in other Lisps, the term "thunk" is used in Scheme to refer to a procedure with no arguments.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The term "proper tail recursion" refers to the property of all Scheme implementations, that they perform tail-call optimization so as to support an indefinite number of active tail calls.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The language is formally defined in the standards R5RS (1998), R6RS (2007), and R7RS (2013).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] They describe standard "forms": keywords and accompanying syntax, which provide the control structure of the language, and standard procedures which perform common tasks.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] This table describes the standard forms in Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Some forms appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Forms marked "L" in this table are classed as derived "library" forms in the standard and are often implemented as macros using more fundamental forms in practice, making the task of implementation much easier than in other languages.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] While `begin` is defined as a library syntax in R5RS, the expander must know about it to achieve the splicing function.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In R6RS it is no longer a library syntax.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The following two tables describe the standard procedures in R5RS Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] R6RS is far more extensive and a summary of this type would not be practical.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Some procedures appear in more than one row because they cannot easily be classified into a single function in the language.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] String and character procedures that contain "-ci" in their names perform case-independent comparisons between their arguments: upper case and lower case versions of the same character are taken to be equal.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Implementations of - and / that take more than two arguments are defined but left optional at R5RS.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Because of Scheme's minimalism, many common procedures and syntactic forms are not defined by the standard.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] In order to keep the core language small but facilitate standardization of extensions, the Scheme community has a "Scheme Request for Implementation" (SRFI) process by which extension libraries are defined through careful discussion of extension proposals.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Many of the SRFIs are supported by all or most Scheme implementations.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The elegant, minimalist design has made Scheme a popular target for language designers, hobbyists, and educators, and because of its small size, that of a typical interpreter, it is also a popular choice for embedded systems and scripting.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The R6RS standard specifies a much broader language, in an attempt to broaden its appeal to programmers.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Almost all implementations provide a traditional Lisp-style read–eval–print loop for development and debugging.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Many also compile Scheme programs to executable binary.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Support for embedding Scheme code in programs written in other languages is also common, as the relative simplicity of Scheme implementations makes it a popular choice for adding scripting capabilities to larger systems developed in languages such as C.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The Gambit, Chicken, and Bigloo Scheme interpreters compile Scheme to C, which makes embedding far easier.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Further, Bigloo's compiler can be configured to generate bytecode for the Java virtual machine (JVM), and has an experimental bytecode generator for .NET.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Some implementations support added features.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] For example, Kawa and JScheme provide integration with Java classes, and the Scheme to C compilers often make it easy to use external libraries written in C, up to allowing the embedding of C code in the Scheme source code.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Another example is Pvts, which offers a set of visual tools that support Scheme learning.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Scheme is widely used by several schools; in particular, several introductory computer science courses use Scheme in conjunction with the textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* (SICP).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] For the past 12 years, PLT has run the ProgramByDesign (formerly TeachScheme!) project, which has exposed close to 600 high school teachers and thousands of high school students to rudimentary Scheme programming.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] MIT's old introductory programming class 6.001 was taught in Scheme, Although 6.001 has been replaced by more modern courses, SICP continues to be taught at MIT.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Likewise, the introductory class at UC Berkeley, CS 61A, was until 2011 taught entirely in Scheme, save minor diversions into Logo to demonstrate dynamic scope.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Today, like MIT, Berkeley has replaced the syllabus with a more modern version that is primarily taught in Python 3, but the current syllabus is still based on the old curriculum, and parts of the class are still taught in Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The textbook *How to Design Programs* is used by some institutes of higher education for their introductory computer science courses.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Worcester Polytechnic Institute uses Scheme exclusively for its introductory course Introduction to Program Design (CS1101).
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology uses Scheme in its more advanced Programming Language Concepts course.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Brandeis University's core course, Structure and Interpretations of Computer Programs (COSI121b), is also taught exclusively in Scheme by theoretical computer scientist Harry Mairson.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] Indiana University's introductory class, C211, is taught entirely in Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] A self-paced version of the course, CS 61AS, continues to use Scheme.
[src:racket/scheme-programming-language] The introductory computer science courses at Yale and Grinnell College are also taught in Scheme.
